    "signals":  [
                    {
                        "number":  "01",
                        "title":  "THE PRICING QUESTION KEPT RETURNING.",
                        "body":  "Several founders returned to the same pricing question: how to move beyond seat-based models when customers increasingly expect outcomes, not access. The conversation moved past frameworks. It became practical â€” and uneasy."
                    },
                    {
                        "number":  "02",
                        "title":  "OPERATIONAL AI HAS A QUIET ADOPTION CURVE.",
                        "body":  "The room agreed: the loud half of the AI conversation has moved past most operators. What remains is unsexy integration work, hiring decisions that look mundane on paper, and slow internal trust-building. Several described this as the actual work of 2026."
                    },
                    {
                        "number":  "03",
                        "title":  "SEVERANCE IS NOW A BRAND EVENT.",
                        "body":  "A pattern emerged in how the room described senior departures: post-LinkedIn, every meaningful exit becomes a 90-day public moment. The discussion turned to severance design, framing language, and the cost of getting it wrong."
                    }
                ],
